    "abstract": "By design, TLS (Transport Layer Security)  is a 2-party, end-to-end protocol.\nYet, in practice, TLS delegation is often deployed: that is, middlebox proxies inspect and even modify TLS traffic between the endpoints.\nRecently, industry-leaders (e.g., Akamai, Cloudflare,  Telefonica, Ericcson), standardization bodies (e.g., IETF, ETSI), and academic researchers have proposed numerous ways of achieving safer TLS delegation.\nWe present LURK the LURK (Limited Use of Remote Keys) extension for TLS~1.2, a suite of designs for  TLS delegation, where the TLS-server is aware of the middlebox.\nWe implement and test LURK. We also cryptographically prove and formally verify, in Proverif, the security of LURK. Finally, we comprehensively analyze how our designs balance (provable) security and  competitive performance.",
    "keywords": [
      "Internet security",
      "Middleboxes",
      "Cryptographic protocols",
      "Transport protocols",
      "TLS",
      "Proverif"
